api_panel_md_js_example:
## Initialize SDK [![github]({{ githubIcon }})](https://github.com/apitable/apitable-sdks)

```js
// If es6 import does not work，use const APITable = require('apitable').default; to replace import { APITable } from "apitable";

const apitable = new APITable({ token: "{{ apiToken }}", fieldKey: "{{ fieldKey }}" });
const datasheet = apitable.datasheet("{{ datasheetId }}");
```

<!--split-->

## Get records

```js

// Get the records from a specific view. Returns the first page of records by default
datasheet.records.query({ viewId: "{{ viewId }}"}).then(response => {
  if (response.success) {
    console.log(response.data);
  } else {
    console.error(response);
  }
});

```

### Returned data example

```json
{{ response }}
```

### Other parameters and tips
```js
/**
 * Global parameter configuration
 */

ew APITable({
  /**
   * (Required) string Your API Token, used for authentication
   */
  token: 'YOUR_API_TOKEN',
  /**
   * (Optional) Globally specify the query of the field and the returned key. By default the column name 'name' is used. When specified as 'id', fieldId will be used as the query and return method (using id can avoid the problem of code failure caused by the modification of the column name)
   */
  fieldKey: 'name', // Defaults
  /**
   * (Optional) Request expiration time
   */
  requestTimeout: 60000, // Default 60000ms (10 seconds)
  /**
   * (Optional) Target server address
   */
  host: 'https://api.aitable.ai/fusion/v1', // Defaults
});

/*******************************/

// Get record
datasheet.record.query({
  /**
   * (Optional) View ID. Defaults to the first view in the APITable. The request will return the filtered/sorted results in the view, and you can use the fields parameter to filter unnecessary field data
   */
  viewId: 'viewId1',
  /**
   * (Optional) Sorts the records of the specified APITable. An array of multiple "sort objects". Supported order: 'asc' and reverse order: 'desc'. Note: The sorting criteria specified by this parameter will override the sorting criteria in the view.
   */
  sort: [{ field: 'field1': order: 'asc' }],
  /**
   * (Optional) An array of recordIds. If this parameter is attached, returns the records array specified in the parameter. The return values are sorted in the order of the passed array. Filtering and sorting are ignored at this time. No pagination, up to 1000 records can be queried each time
   */
  recordIds: ['recordId1', 'recordId2'],
  /**
   * (Optional) Specify the field to be returned (the default is the field name, and it can also be specified as the field Id by fieldKey). If this parameter is attached, the returned record collection will be filtered, and only the specified fields will be returned.
   */
  fields: ['title', 'detail', 'Number of references'],
  /**
   * (Optional) Use formulas as filter conditions to return matching records. Visit https://help.aitable.ai/docs/guide/tutorial-getting-started-with-formulas to learn how to use formulas
   */
  filterByFormula: '{Number of references} >  0',
  /**
   * (Optional) Limit the total number of records returned. If this value is less than the actual total number of records in the table, the total number of records returned will be limited to this value.
   */
  maxRecords: 5000,
  /**
   * (Optional) Cell value type, the default is 'json', when 'string' is specified, all values will be automatically converted to string format.
   */
  cellFormat: 'json',
  /**
   * (Optional) Specify the query of the field and the returned key. By default the column name 'name' is used. When specified as 'id', fieldId will be used as the query and return method (using id can avoid the problem of code failure caused by the modification of the column name)
   */
  fieldKey: 'name',
});

/*******************************/

/**
 * It is the same as query to obtain record parameters, and automatically handles pagination. until all the data is obtained.
 */
const allRecordsIter = datasheet.records.queryAll()
for await (const eachPageRecords of allRecordsIter) {
  console.log(eachPageRecords)
}
```

<!--split-->

## Add records
```js
// The add method receives an array value, and can create multiple records at the same time, and a single request can create up to 10 records
datasheet.records.create({{ records }}).then(response => {
  if (response.success) {
    console.log(response.data);
  } else {
    console.error(response);
  }
})
```

### Returned data example

```json
{{ response }}
```


### Other parameters and tips

The add interface receives an array value that can create multiple records simultaneously, up to 10 records per request

<!--split-->

## Update records
```js
/**
* update receives an array value, multiple records can be updated at the same time, and a single request can update up to 10 records
* Special Note: update will only update the data under the fields you passed in, and will not affect the unpassed fields. If you need to clear the value, please pass in null explicitly
*/
datasheet.records.update({{ records }}).then(response => {
  if (response.success) {
    console.log(response.data);
  } else {
    console.error(response);
  }
})
```
### Returned data example
```json
{{ response }}
```


### Other parameters and tips

The update interface receives an array value, which can update multiple records at the same time, and a single request can update up to 10 records
Special attention: update will only update the data under the fields you passed in, and will not affect the data that is not passed in. If you need to clear the value, please pass in null explicitly

<!--split-->

## Delete records
```js
// The del method receives an array value and can delete multiple records at the same time. A single request can delete up to 10 records
datasheet.records.delete({{ recordIds }}).then(response => {
  if (response.success) {
    console.log(response.data);
  } else {
    console.error(response);
  }
})
```
### Returned data example
```json
{
  "code": 200,
  "success": true,
  "message": "success"
}
```
### Other parameters and tips
The delete interface receives an array value, which can delete multiple records at the same time, and a single request can delete up to 10 records

<!--split-->

## Upload attachments

```js
/*
* Get the file from the file input
* <input id="input" name="file" type="file" accept="*" >
* Or use streams to read files in NodeJs
* const file = fs.createReadStream(/your/file/path)
*
* The browser environment is used as an example below
*/
const input = document.getElementById('input');

input.onchange = function () {
  const file = this.files[0];
  datasheet.upload(file).then(response => {
    /**
     * response 
     *   success: boolean
     *   code: number
     *   message: string
     *   data: IAttachment
     */
    if (response.success) {
      console.log(response.data);
    } else {
      console.error(response);
    }
  });
};

```
### Returned data example

*Tips: After uploading, please write the data in data to the attachment cell as soon as possible, otherwise the attachment link may become invalid*

